Learning Generative AI From Scratch
In Part 28, we built our first RAG application.

10 min read
Just now

--

Press enter or click to view image in full size

We took a document, passed it to an AI, and got back answers that felt surprisingly accurate and grounded.
I remember feeling genuinely impressed the first time it worked.
Then I tried it with a longer document — a 40-page PDF — and something strange happened. Some answers were perfect. Others were completely wrong, even though the correct information was clearly sitting somewhere in the document.
Same RAG pipeline. Same AI model. Completely inconsistent results.
I spent two days trying to figure out what was broken.
It turned out nothing was broken. The problem was something I hadn’t thought about at all when building the pipeline — something so fundamental that getting it wrong quietly breaks everything downstream.
The problem was how I was splitting the document.
That’s what this article is about. Chunking — the step that happens before retrieval, before embedding, before any AI magic — and why getting it wrong is one of the most common reasons RAG applications fail in production.

What Is Chunking?
Before an AI can answer questions about your documents, those documents need to go through a preparation process.
You can’t take a 200-page technical manual and hand it directly to an LLM. Two reasons:
First, LLMs have context window limits. Even large context models have boundaries, and filling the entire context with a massive document is expensive, slow, and often counterproductive.
Second — and this is the one most people miss — you need to retrieve the right pieces of a document, not the whole thing. RAG works by finding the chunks most relevant to a user’s question and sending only those to the model. If your chunks are poorly formed, retrieval finds the wrong pieces, and the model answers based on the wrong context.
Chunking is the process of splitting a large document into smaller, retrievable pieces called chunks.
Simple idea. Surprisingly hard to do well.

Why Chunking Matters More Than Most Tutorials Admit
Here’s something I wish someone had told me earlier: chunking is not a preprocessing detail. It’s a core architectural decision.
Every chunk becomes its own embedding — its own point in vector space. When a user asks a question, the retrieval system finds the chunks whose embeddings are closest to the question’s embedding.
This means:

• If a chunk is too large, it contains multiple topics and its embedding becomes a blurry average of all of them — making it harder to retrieve precisely.

• If a chunk is too small, it loses context — a sentence like “This is caused by the issue described above” means nothing without the surrounding paragraphs.

• If a chunk splits mid-sentence or mid-thought, the retrieved piece is incomplete and confuses the model.
The 40-page PDF problem I described at the beginning? My chunks were splitting paragraphs mid-sentence. The model was receiving fragments that started with “…which is why the configuration must be set before deployment” — with no context for what “this” referred to.
Fixing the chunking strategy fixed the retrieval quality immediately.

The 5 Main Chunking Strategies
Let me walk through each strategy the way I actually learned them — by understanding what problem each one was designed to solve.

Strategy 1: Fixed-Size Chunking
What it is:
Split the document every N characters or tokens, regardless of where sentences or paragraphs end.
public List<String> fixedSizeChunk(String text, int chunkSize, int overlap) {
List<String> chunks = new ArrayList<>();
int start = 0; while (start < text.length()) {
int end = Math.min(start + chunkSize, text.length());
chunks.add(text.substring(start, end));
start += chunkSize - overlap; // overlap slides the window
}
return chunks;
}
When it works:
Large volumes of relatively uniform text — log files, plain data, simple content where exact sentence boundaries don’t matter much.
When it fails:
Narrative text, technical documentation, anything where meaning is carried across sentence and paragraph boundaries. Splitting “The configuration must be set before…” in the middle of a sentence destroys the chunk’s usefulness for retrieval.
The overlap parameter:
Notice the overlap in the code above. This is a partial fix for the mid-sentence splitting problem — by repeating N characters between consecutive chunks, you reduce the chance that a critical idea gets split across two chunks with no continuity. A typical overlap is 10–20% of chunk size.

Strategy 2: Recursive Character Splitting
What it is:
Split on a priority list of separators — try paragraph breaks first, then sentence breaks, then word breaks, then characters — until chunks are within your target size.
public List<String> recursiveChunk(String text, int maxChunkSize) {
// Priority order: paragraph → sentence → word → character
String[] separators = {"\n\n", "\n", ". ", " ", ""};
return splitRecursively(text, separators, maxChunkSize);
}private List<String> splitRecursively(String text,
String[] separators,
int maxSize) {
List<String> chunks = new ArrayList<>();
if (text.length() <= maxSize) {
chunks.add(text.trim());
return chunks;
}
String separator = separators[0];
String[] parts = text.split(Pattern.quote(separator), -1);
StringBuilder current = new StringBuilder();
for (String part : parts) {
if (current.length() + part.length() + separator.length() <= maxSize) {
if (current.length() > 0) current.append(separator);
current.append(part);
} else {
if (current.length() > 0) {
chunks.add(current.toString().trim());
current = new StringBuilder();
}
if (part.length() > maxSize && separators.length > 1) {
// Recurse with next separator
chunks.addAll(splitRecursively(part,
Arrays.copyOfRange(separators, 1, separators.length),
maxSize));
} else {
current.append(part);
}
}
}
if (current.length() > 0) chunks.add(current.toString().trim());
return chunks;
}
When it works:
General-purpose text — blog posts, articles, documentation, emails. This is the most commonly used strategy in production RAG systems because it respects natural language structure while still enforcing size limits.
Why it’s better than fixed-size:
It tries to keep sentences and paragraphs intact, which means chunks have coherent meaning and produce better embeddings.

Strategy 3: Document-Structure-Aware Chunking
What it is:
Use the document’s own structure — headings, sections, HTML tags, Markdown headers — as chunk boundaries.
public List<String> recursiveChunk(String text, int maxChunkSize) {
// Priority order: paragraph → sentence → word → character
String[] separators = {"\n\n", "\n", ". ", " ", ""};
return splitRecursively(text, separators, maxChunkSize);
}private List<String> splitRecursively(String text,
String[] separators,
int maxSize) {
List<String> chunks = new ArrayList<>();
if (text.length() <= maxSize) {
chunks.add(text.trim());
return chunks;
}
String separator = separators[0];
String[] parts = text.split(Pattern.quote(separator), -1);
StringBuilder current = new StringBuilder();
for (String part : parts) {
if (current.length() + part.length() + separator.length() <= maxSize) {
if (current.length() > 0) current.append(separator);
current.append(part);
} else {
if (current.length() > 0) {
chunks.add(current.toString().trim());
current = new StringBuilder();
}
if (part.length() > maxSize && separators.length > 1) {
// Recurse with next separator
chunks.addAll(splitRecursively(part,
Arrays.copyOfRange(separators, 1, separators.length),
maxSize));
} else {
current.append(part);
}
}
}
if (current.length() > 0) chunks.add(current.toString().trim());
return chunks;
}
When it works:
Structured documents — technical documentation, wikis, API references, Markdown files, HTML pages with clear heading hierarchies.
The key insight:
Notice that each chunk includes the header (currentHeader + "\n" + content). This is critical — a chunk that says "Returns a 404 error when the resource is not found" is far more retrievable when it's prefixed with "## Error Handling" than when it appears as an isolated sentence.
When it fails:
Unstructured text — scanned PDFs, plain prose, documents with no clear formatting hierarchy.

Strategy 4: Semantic Chunking
What it is:
Instead of splitting on size or structure, split when the meaning of the text changes significantly — detected by comparing embedding similarity between consecutive sentences.
public List<String> semanticChunk(List<String> sentences,
EmbeddingService embedder,
double similarityThreshold) {
List<String> chunks = new ArrayList<>();
List<float[]> embeddings = embedder.embedAll(sentences); List<String> currentChunk = new ArrayList<>();
currentChunk.add(sentences.get(0));
for (int i = 1; i < sentences.size(); i++) {
double similarity = cosineSimilarity(
embeddings.get(i - 1),
embeddings.get(i)
);
if (similarity >= similarityThreshold) {
// Similar topic — keep in same chunk
currentChunk.add(sentences.get(i));
} else {
// Topic shift detected — start new chunk
chunks.add(String.join(" ", currentChunk));
currentChunk = new ArrayList<>();
currentChunk.add(sentences.get(i));
}
}
if (!currentChunk.isEmpty()) {
chunks.add(String.join(" ", currentChunk));
}
return chunks;
}
private double cosineSimilarity(float[] a, float[] b) {
double dot = 0, normA = 0, normB = 0;
for (int i = 0; i < a.length; i++) {
dot += a[i] * b[i];
normA += a[i] * a[i];
normB += b[i] * b[i];
}
return dot / (Math.sqrt(normA) * Math.sqrt(normB));
}
When it works:
Long, complex documents where topics shift organically — research papers, legal documents, lengthy reports. Each chunk naturally contains one coherent topic, which makes embeddings much more precise.
The trade-off:
This strategy requires embedding every sentence during preprocessing — which is computationally expensive compared to the simpler strategies. For small document sets it’s fine. For millions of documents, the cost adds up quickly.

Strategy 5: Agentic / Proposition-Based Chunking
What it is:
Use an LLM itself to break a document into atomic, self-contained propositions — statements that each carry complete meaning without requiring surrounding context.
Example input paragraph:
“Spring AI supports multiple vector stores. Pinecone is recommended for production. Chroma is better for local development.”
After proposition chunking:

• “Spring AI supports multiple vector stores.”

• “Pinecone vector store is recommended for production use with Spring AI.”

• “Chroma vector store is better suited for local development with Spring AI.”
Notice how each proposition is expanded to be fully self-contained — “Pinecone” alone means little without the context of Spring AI and production use.
public List<String> propositionChunk(String paragraph,
ChatClient chatClient) {
String prompt = """
Break the following paragraph into atomic propositions.
Each proposition must be:
- A single complete fact or statement
- Fully self-contained (understandable without surrounding context)
- Expanded to include necessary context from the paragraph Return one proposition per line, no numbering, no bullets.
Paragraph:
""" + paragraph;
String response = chatClient.prompt()
.user(prompt)
.call()
.content();
return Arrays.stream(response.split("\n"))
.map(String::trim)
.filter(s -> !s.isEmpty())
.collect(Collectors.toList());
}
When it works:
High-precision retrieval requirements — medical information, legal documents, technical FAQs where a half-answer is as bad as a wrong answer.
The trade-off:
Expensive — you’re calling an LLM for every paragraph during preprocessing. But the retrieval precision improvement is significant enough that for critical applications, it’s worth it.

Choosing the Right Strategy — A Decision Framework
This is the question I actually had to answer when building production systems, and there’s no single right answer — it depends on your document type and performance requirements.
